e":"1176–Deceased","1156–1230":"1156–1230","1201–1266":"1201–1266","1151–1211":"1151–1211","1151–Female":"1151–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1211":"1211","1266":"1266","1156":"1156","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1151":"1151","Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England":"Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"West","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: from Middle English, Middle High German <i>west</i> ‘west’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived to the west of a settlement, or a habitational name for someone who had migrated from further west.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Vesterinen</b>: from the personal name <i>Vesteri</i> (a short form of   Sylvester  ) + the surname suffix <i>-nen</i>.","History: This name was brought to North America independently by many bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Thomas West, 12th Baron De La Warre, was captain general of Virginia in 1610–11. The state of DE is named for him. One of the earliest permanent settlers was Francis West (1606–92), who came to Duxbury, MA, from Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, in or before 1638."],"variants":[{"name":"Western","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>westerne</i> ‘western’, denoting ‘(the man from the) west’. Compare   West   and   Wester  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Vestern, found in two places, a compound of <i>vest</i> ‘west’ + <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’, denoting a farm to the west."]},{"name":"Sylvester","meanings":["English and German: from the Middle English and Latin personal name <i>Silvester</i> ‘dweller in the forest’ (a derivative of <i>silva</i> ‘wood’). The name was borne by three popes, including a contemporary of Constantine the Great, and seems to have been first used in England by clerics."]},{"name":"Westman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Birgit, Erik, Hilmer, Nels.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from (an altered form of) the elements <i>väst</i> ‘west’ + <i>-man</i>. It is also found in Finland.","Americanized form of German <b>Westmann</b>: variant of   West  , with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Everard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was reinforced at the time of the Norman Conquest by a Continental Germanic form introduced to Britain by the Normans. The modern given name may be a transferred use of the surname, but it was in regular use in the Digby family of Rutland from the 15th to the 17th centuries, probably as a survival of the Norman name. It alternated in this family with   Kenelm ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":39,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":48,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":83,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Fitz Everard de West was born in 1176, in Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England, his father, Ralph de Gaste, was 25 and his mother, Lady Ralph de Gaste, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Lady Jane Neily. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1176–":"1176–Surnud","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1156–1230":"1156–1230","1201–1266":"1201–1266","1151–1211":"1151–1211","1151–Female":"1151–Surnud","1259":"1